**2. Wire it up in `Program.cs`:**

```csharp
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Register Problem Details services
builder.Services.AddProblemDetails();
builder.Services.AddExceptionHandler<ExceptionToProblemDetailsHandler>();

var app = builder.Build();

// Must be early in the pipeline
app.UseExceptionHandler();

// Your endpoints below...
app.MapGet("/example/{id}", (int id) =>
{
    if (id < 0) throw new ArgumentException("ID must be positive");
    if (id == 0) throw new KeyNotFoundException("Item not found");
    if (id == 99) throw new InvalidOperationException("Cannot process this item");
    return Results.Ok(new { Id = id, Name = "Test" });
});

app.Run();
```

**How it works:**

- `IExceptionHandler` (available since .NET 8) intercepts all unhandled exceptions globally — no per-endpoint try-catch needed
- The `switch` expression maps exception types to HTTP status codes
- For 500s, the real exception message is hidden; only a generic message is returned
- A `traceId` is included for correlating logs to responses

**Example 404 response:**

```json
{
  "status": 404,
  "title": "Resource Not Found",
  "detail": "Item not found",
  "instance": "/example/0",
  "traceId": "00-abc123..."
}
```

This requires **.NET 8+**. For .NET 7, you'd use `app.UseExceptionHandler("/error")` with a fallback endpoint instead of `IExceptionHandler`.
